<br>
<h1> <center>Intent or Intention Mining </center></h1>
<h3> <center>Mining Various Types of Intents Expressed in Social Media Posts</center></h1>
<br>
<br>
<b><span style="font-size:20pt"><font color=#ff0000>Textbook:</font>
"<a href="https://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/FBS/sentiment-opinion-emotion-analysis.html">Sentiment Analysis: mining sentiments, opinions, and emotions</a>."
by Bing Liu, 2015. </span></b><br/>
<ul> 
<li>Chapter 11 of the book focuses on intent mining, which is closely related to sentiment.
</ul>

<p>
<span style="font-size:18pt"><b>Definition</b>: Intent or intention has two main meanings or senses:</span><br/>

<ol>
<li> A course of action that a person or a group of persons intends to follow.

<li> The goal or purpose behind a specific action or set of actions.
</ol>
<p> The aim of this project is to mine different intents or intentions from social media posts based on the text content of the posts. There is a slight difference in meaning between intent and intention, but for our practical mining purpose, they are interchangeable. 

<br><br>
<h3> Publications </h3>

<ul>

<p> <li> Zhiyuan Chen, Bing Liu, Meichun Hsu, Malu Castellanos, and Riddhiman Ghosh. <a href="http://www.cs.uic.edu/~liub/publications/NAACL-2013-Zhiyuan-Intention.pdf">Identifying Intention Posts in Discussion Forums</a>. <i>Proceedings of The 2013 Conference of the North American Chapter of the Association for Computational Linguistics: Human Language Technologies (NAACL-HLT-2013)</i>, June 9-15, 2013, Atlanta, USA.   

</p>
</ul>
